      "writtenOn": "2026-02-24T15:25:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This default implementation is creating a brand-new consumer for every existing consumer.\nIf I call this method twice with the same consumer, I\u0027ll get two different consumer instances.\n\nIs there any value in having this default implementation?\n\nIf not, why not just throw an `UnsupportedMethodException` instead?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 107,
        "startChar": 24,
        "endLine": 107,
        "endChar": 78
      },
      "revId": "273162b6d5404474d678876c6b76ec7957d7a880",
      "serverId": "173816e5-2b9a-37c3-8a2e-48639d4f1153"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "93cfb654_d1589810",
        "filename": "src/main/java/com/gerritforge/gerrit/eventbroker/BrokerApi.java",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1072905
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-02-24T17:54:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The reason for adding these default implementations is to avoid forcing all existing brokers to adopt the new API in a big-bang change,  preserving the current behaviour for brokers that don\u0027t yet support message context.\n\nIf we were to throw an `UnsupportedOperationException` instead, existing broker implementations would still compile and deploy without issues, but would then fail at runtime as soon as someone uses the new methods (i.e. multi-site, websession-broker, pull-replication, and so forth).\n\nI think we should either require all brokers to implement the new API (and fail fast at compile time) or allow existing brokers to continue working unchanged, via the default implementations.\n\nI chose the latter, but we can discuss furhter.",
      "parentUuid": "33a21d64_179a1fb3",
